Hibiscus

Hibiscus sabdariffa

Medicinal Plants
Author: E. Montalvo-Gonzlez
Published: 01/09/2022
Read Time: 4 minutes
Category: Medicinal Plants
Location: Pune

Description

Hibiscus sabdariffa, commonly known as Roselle, is an erect, mostly branched annual shrub that can grow up to 3.5 meters tall. Its stem has a reddish hue, and it possesses a deep-reaching taproot that helps in drought tolerance. The plant features large, deeply lobed leaves, which are typically green but can also exhibit reddish tinges, adding to its vivid tropical appeal. The leaves are alternately arranged, broad, and glossy.The flowers of Hibiscus sabdariffa are large, with a diameter of about 3 to 6 inches, and can be red, yellow, or white, often having a dark center containing short peduncles. The petals are bell-shaped, with some varieties bearing single or double rows of petals, and the blooms are short-lived, lasting only a day.


Medicinal Properties

Antioxidant Anti-inflammatory Antihypertensive Antimicrobial Antidiabetic Diuretic Hepatoprotective

Common Uses

  • 1)Lowering high blood pressure
  • 2)Managing cholesterol levels
  • 3)Treating inflammation and infections
  • 4(Improving liver health
  • 5)Supporting weight management
  • 6)Enhancing digestion
  • 7)Boosting immune system

Growing Information

Growing Conditions

Warm tropical or subtropical climate, well-drained loamy soil, full sun exposure, regular watering, moderate humidity, space for bushy growth.

Water Requirements

Regular watering, keep soil moist but avoid water stagnation.

Temperature Range

20C to 30C optimum

Harvesting Tips

Harvest the calyces (flower sepals) when they turn deep red and before they fully dry on the plant to retain maximum medicinal potency.

Preparation Methods

Dry the calyces and grind into powder for tea or capsules. Calyces can also be boiled in water to prepare herbal tea decoctions. Extracts can be made by soaking dried parts in water or alcohol for tinctures or gels.

Medicinal preparations of Hibiscus sabdariffa primarily use the dried calyces (flower sepals), which are rich in bioactive compounds including anthocyanins, flavonoids, and organic acids responsible for its therapeutic effects. The common medicinal preparation methods include:Decoction/Herbal Tea: The dried calyces are boiled in water for 10-15 minutes to extract the pigment and medicinal compounds, producing a red-colored herbal tea known as "Hibiscus tea" or "Zobo" which can be consumed hot or cold. Powder: The dried calyces are crushed into a fine powder which can be directly used as a tea base or encapsulated for oral medicinal use.

Chemical Compounds

Anthocyanins Hibiscus acid Flavonoids Phenolic acids Vitamin C Organic acids
